text: The twist ending is that the 'grandparents' are actually pagan gods that the children's mother sacrifices her children to every twenty/thirty years or so in exchange for youth. Using her new youth, the mother then goes out and gets herself a new man in order to have more kids, so that the cycle can start again. You will see this in paintings, photographic evidence, and other found footage that the children will find in the 'grandparents' house... showing that the mother and 'grandparents' have been alive for years and years, and that other children have been sacrificed before them.  The movie will end with the mother dumping all the kids electronics onto the pile with the other evidence of her past lives and children, then waltzing out a younger women. ... the only question is, will the mother and 'grandparents' be enough "with the times" to know that content posted over the internet isn't so easily disposed of? Will they finally be caught, or will the children's sacrifice, and the youth it gives them, have altered ALL of their appearances enough that they can claim that they aren't the old couple and mother shown in the videos? We will see....  P.S. I just made all this up, but it's my official head-cannon until the movie comes out. XD

text: I'm surprised that not only is this guy still allowed to make movies in Hollywood but that his name is advertised as if that's a reason to go see it. I enjoyed his first two films too but they were a long time ago and his name is poison to a film's credibility at this stage, surely. People have been shunted into the wilderness of Hollywood for far less egregious turds than Shyamalan has been responsible for so why does he keep coming back and making awful movies? This looks like a crappy film with bad writing (I bet he wrote the script) and awkward performances. So par for the course then.

text: Spoilers in case no one wants to find out. Found out from someone who went to a screening to the movie.            the mom sends them off to there "grandparents" house as she wanted to go on a vacation with her boyfriend. the first 3 days it shows them being happy with the grandparents but one night they see their grandmother running around naked in the house and scratching the wall but they think she has a disability of some sort.The twist begins when the grandmother is cooking and she drops hot oil on the daughters laptop camera and because of that whenever they skype there mother she cant see whats happening.Then eventually she fixes it two days after and when they talk to there mother her mother is worried because of whats happening in the house.Then the son puts the laptop on the camera on the window to show what there doing and its then when they found out that theyre not the grandparents.Then the movie gets tense and the chasing scenes start and in the end the daughter goes in the basement to see two dead bodies.Its their actual grandparents. and then it ends with the two killing the grandparents and in the end the police come.  Overall the "grandparents" were mental patients who escaped and killed their actual ones.

text: Honestly I believe that this movie is very original, in the idea of the antagonist being the elderly. Most horror movies use the super natural as the antagonist and this movie went the complete opposite direction. The use of the elderly as a insane couple is completely realistic and therefore makes the overall movie Better. Also the plot twist of the elderly becoming the antagonist after originally being normal is great. As well for the protagonist having connections to the outside world makes the plot even better. I honestly wished that instead the parents ignoring the problem didn't happen but hopefully that's another plot twist which the way it was shown in the trailer makes it a complete possibility. Although the movie may seem a bit uninteresting I'm looking forward to watching this movie.

text: I bet that the two kids are already dead, and the grandpa wants to keep them from finding out because he's Mr. Glass.  The grandma is clearly the devil, and has been driven insane by plant chemicals.  However, she's deathly allergic to water.  After driving her away with a garden hose, the kids will flee to the outskirts of the town.  They will then be run over by a starship, because the whole movie is actually taking place in 2315.  WHAT A TWIST! * * * * * Nah, but seriously:  The movie is probably going to be a modern-day twist on the Hansel and Gretel myth.  On the teaser poster, one of "Grandma's Rules" is "eat as much as you want".  She's trying to fatten the children up for the slaughter (see the boy flexing his muscles at 0:30).  Her asking the girl to climb into the oven to clean it is another obvious reference.  The mom's nonchalant attitude toward the whole affair is also significant; in the original tale of Hansel and Gretel, their mother is the one who comes up with the plot to abandon them in the woods.  The twist will be that she was in on the grandmother's plan all along, as several others have already predicted.  It's an interesting concept, but I'm definitely waiting for the reviews to come in before I decide to see it.  Mr. Shyamalan has made too many mistakes to get the benefit of the doubt from me anymore.

text: Ok so I just got back from seeing this movie so here are my thoughts free of spoilers. At first I did not really like this film. I honestly thought it more of a comedy with a few predictable jump scares in between. Most of which made me laugh or just sit in my seat emotionless but I will admit, the humor is pretty good. As for horror, aside from the jump scares I mentioned before, there isn't that much to see. Although about an hour or so in, things start to get a little more freaky and actually got me a bit suspenseful and exited. I wanted to see what was going to happen next. As for the plot twist, (which I will not spoil here) it was actually really good. I did not see it coming at all (that's probably just me and my friends though). Overall I'd give this movie a watch but just don't go into it expecting anything big.
